    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/00087019502579875572" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Philippa</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/09/before-you-know-it/#comment-21681"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-10-15T18:36:42-04:00">Friday, October 15, 2010 at 6:36 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I was an au pair in France years ago, and the woman who employed me gave me only the food her kids wouldn&#39;t eat. Some of it was pretty good, but some was burnt or stale &#8212; she was still living through WWII and had a desperate need not to waste anything. Your blog brought back some interesting memories. But the recipe was wonderful. </p>
<p>I adore sharp flavours and could probably drink a really good vinaigrette straight from the container, some days. </p>
<p>I don&#39;t bake (used to but somehow lost the will), and although I love the stories in your blog and your book, it&#39;s the savoury recipes I try. Thanks for this.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-21681' data-commentid="21681" data-postid="741" data-belowelement="comment-21681" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Philippa" aria-label='Reply to Philippa'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-21682" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/09/before-you-know-it/#comment-21682"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-10-28T23:02:28-04:00">Thursday, October 28, 2010 at 11:02 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Leeks are lovely &#038; this was good, once I found small leeks.  Everyone at the farmers&#39; markets here seems to think that bigger is better (just like they think white corn is preferable to yellow) &#8212; I finally found one bunch of 6 that included 3 about the diameter of a quarter, but it was a search.</p>
<p>The little leeks did indeed become sweet after 10 minutes in boiling salted water, &#038; were very nice with the vinaigrette &#038; hardboiled egg garnish.</p>
<p>I like the idea of a poached egg too, maybe like eggs benedict, on a bed of leeks atop an English muffin with the vinaigrette poured over &#038; lots of coarse black pepper.</p>
<p>I didn&#39;t have shallots, so made the vinaigrette with a green onion.  There&#39;s a little left over &#038; I&#39;m going to use it on steamed whitefish with brown rice (wish I had some leftover leeks to go with that).</p>
<p>Thanks for another nice, useful recipe.</p>
    </div>

